      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-13T17:21:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The standard syntax for generic[1] function calls is to sandwich the type argument between the function name and the argument list, e.g. hello\u003cstring\u003e(\"world\").\n\nTry this:\n\n  $$\u003cHTMLDialogElement\u003e(#strategyChangeDialog\", this)\n\nThen you can drop the outer parentheses and write this directly:\n\n  $$\u003cHTMLDialogElement\u003e(#strategyChangeDialog\", this)?.close();\n\nActually, optional chaining (?.) will fail silently[1] if for some reason the #strategyChangeDialog isn\u0027t found, but you probably want a loud error on the console since this almost surely indicates a bug.\n\nFor that reason it might be better to use (!.), which tells the compiler to assume that the left hand is non-null[2], and will cause a runtime error if that\u0027s not true:\n\n    $$\u003cHTMLDialogElement\u003e(#strategyChangeDialog\", this)!.close();\n\n[1] https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/generics.html#hello-world-of-generics\n[2] https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-3-7.html#optional-chaining\n[3] https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-0.html#non-null-assertion-operator",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 625,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 625,
        "endChar": 57
      },
      "revId": "ba8ffd4447af5eec7dff2130a69e2e3a3ab848b3",
